	<section class="comments" id="comments">
		<h2 class="comments-header">Comments</h2>
		
			<div class='comment'>
				<h3 class='comment-date'>Submitted 02/16/2011</h3>
				<div class='comment-main'>
					<div class='comment-content'>Has a small scale management by exception strategy been tried by targeting an enrollment of volunteer patients from the top 25% of the most chronically ill (the ones needing an trusted advocate in a Balkanized delivery system)? This could utilize a dedicated Advanced Nurse Navigator to conduct on behalf of the participants a longitudinal coordination of their clinical continuum of care, while being supported by an EHR, with administrative and cost data being supplied directly by the claims payer of record, the private clinical data being supplied by the providers, based on a HIPAA release from the patient and hosted by the plan sponsor (the beneficiary of the significant financial savings described in your article).</div>
					<p class='comment-author'>Edwin Childs, MHA</p>
										<p class='comment-disclosure'><span class='comment-disclosure-label'>Disclosure/Conflict of Interest:</span> None</p>
				</div><!--/.comment-main -->
			</div><!--/.comment -->
			<div class='comment'>
				<h3 class='comment-date'>Submitted 09/03/2010</h3>
				<div class='comment-main'>
					<div class='comment-content'>What a shame that the current opportunity was not taken to give all the Federally Qualified Community Health Centers across the country a single high quality EMR that would be well equipped to collect the important reports, the ease of tracking chronic illness, safety concerns, and all the other components of a robust EMR.</div>
					<p class='comment-author'>Sarah Gregg, </p>
						<p class='comment-position'>QI Coordinator</p>
											<p class='comment-affiliation'>Henry J. Austin Health Center</p>
					<p class='comment-disclosure'><span class='comment-disclosure-label'>Disclosure/Conflict of Interest:</span> Not stated</p>
				</div><!--/.comment-main -->
			</div><!--/.comment -->
			<div class='comment'>
				<h3 class='comment-date'>Submitted 09/22/2010</h3>
				<div class='comment-main'>
					<div class='comment-content'>The existence of EHRs certainly provides some of the infrastructure. However, the ability to collect and integrate data from providers for patients with chronic conditions will also be required. The Health Information Exchanges enable the sharing of data, but some providers must take the responsibility to see that the data are integrated. The calculation of the meaningful use measures relevant to chronic conditions should help.</div>
					<p class='comment-author'>Daniel Ries, PhD</p>
						<p class='comment-position'>Consultant and Educator</p>
											<p class='comment-affiliation'>Tiadata Consulting and Northeastern University</p>
					<p class='comment-disclosure'><span class='comment-disclosure-label'>Disclosure/Conflict of Interest:</span> Not stated</p>
				</div><!--/.comment-main -->
			</div><!--/.comment -->
